Abstract
This paper introduces a generative, model-based reinforcement learning framework for
algorithmic trading that fundamentally departs from traditional reactive models. The core
of our system is a deep Generative World Model, trained to learn the underlying dynam-
ics of financial markets. This allows the trading agent to perform large-scale simulations of
potential future state trajectories contingent on its actions. Decision-making is thus trans-
formed from a reactive policy based on the present state to a planning process (e.g., Monte
Carlo Tree Search) that optimizes for the highest expected utility over a distribution of
simulated futures. We introduce a novel Reflexivity Vector into the state representation
to explicitly model and navigate self-referential market feedback loops. The framework’s
robustness is validated not with a standard backtest, but through an Adversarial Backtest,
where its performance is measured against an agent trained to actively exploit its strategy.
The results demonstrate superior alpha generation and resilience, suggesting that a genera-
tive, predictive approach provides a significant advantage in navigating complex, adaptive
financial systems.
