B The Reflexivity Vector
The components of the Reflexivity Vector Rt are designed to be computationally tractable
proxies for complex, self-referential market phenomena.
• Strategy Discourse Metric (Dt): This is computed by tracking a curated list of keywords
and n-grams related to popular trading strategies (e.g., ”risk parity”, ”gamma squeeze”,
”HFT scalping”) across a corpus of financial news (e.g., Reuters, Bloomberg) and social
media (e.g., Twitter API). The metric is a time-weighted sum of the frequency of these
terms, giving more weight to recent mentions.
Dt =
i∈keywords j∈corpus
e−λ(t−tj ) ·freq(i,j)
where λis a decay factor.
• Crowdedness Indicator (Ct): This metric synthesizes two data sources. First, it uses
publicly available 13F filings to determine the concentration of institutional ownership in
an asset. Second, it calculates the net speculative positioning (longs minus shorts) from
the Commitment of Traders (COT) reports for futures markets and the put/call ratio for
options markets. These are normalized and combined into a single score.
• Model Correlation (ρM(t)): To compute this, we first simulate the signals of sev-
eral well-known ”vanilla” quantitative strategies (e.g., a 50/200-day moving average
crossover, a relative strength index (RSI) momentum strategy). We then calculate a
rolling correlation between the historical signal series of these vanilla strategies and the
signal series generated by our own agent G. A high and rising correlation suggests our
agent’s logic is converging with the market consensus, indicating a crowded trade and
high reflexive risk.
